WEBVTT

00:00:00.031 --> 00:00:02.281
At the Hyatt Regency, the deadly change

00:00:02.281 --> 00:00:03.617
looked like a shortcut.

00:00:04.599 --> 00:00:06.714
The walkway design used one continuous

00:00:06.714 --> 00:00:08.760
hanger rod from roof to fourth floor

00:00:08.760 --> 00:00:11.931
to second floor. In shop drawings,

00:00:11.931 --> 00:00:14.009
it became two shorter rods.

00:00:14.009 --> 00:00:17.107
Easier to build. But the load path

00:00:17.107 --> 00:00:20.310
changed. The fourth-floor connection now

00:00:20.310 --> 00:00:22.088
carried both walkways, not one.

00:00:22.850 --> 00:00:24.772
The load essentially doubled.

00:00:24.888 --> 00:00:28.337
NBS later found the original design was

00:00:28.337 --> 00:00:31.786
already weak; the revision left roughly

00:00:31.786 --> 00:00:34.921
one-third of code-expected capacity.

00:00:34.921 --> 00:00:38.266
On July 17, 1981, two walkways collapsed

00:00:38.266 --> 00:00:40.251
during a crowded dance.

00:00:40.251 --> 00:00:43.700
Official records count 113 dead and 186

00:00:43.700 --> 00:00:46.354
injured. This was not a shop detail.

00:00:46.395 --> 00:00:49.207
It was a structural redesign.

00:00:50.192 --> 00:00:52.261
Every handoff treated it like paperwork.

00:00:52.863 --> 00:00:55.957
Small causes, massive consequences.
